                <opener>
                    <dateline>March 28, 1932.</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It seems to all of us here that the next book which you should publish should be <hi rend="caps">THE SONG OF THE MESSIAH</hi>. The most important work that you have done, and are going to do, is this <hi rend="caps">"SONG"</hi> cycle, in my opinion, and it has been a long time since we have had a volume in the cycle. What I would like to do would be to send you a contract for <hi rend="caps">THE SONG OF THE MESSIAH</hi> at once, stipulating that this is to be your next book, and agreeing to pay you, on signing of the contract, an advance of $250.00 on account of a royalty of 10% to 2500, 12½% on the next 2500, 15% thereafter. We should wish to include in this contract an option on the book of Indian tales which you proposed in your letter of March 14th, which might very suitably follow <hi rend="caps">THE SONG OF THE MESSIAH</hi>, but we do believe that it is to your advantage to make <hi rend="caps">THE SONG OF THE MESSIAH</hi> the next volume.</p>
                
                <p>What do you say to all this?</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>HS Latham</signed>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
